From: PS4 Linux Baikal Port <noreply@ps4-linux>
Subject: [PATCH] amdgpu: v60 - also skip TX ENABLE on Liverpool DP

The v59 boot (patch 0031, skip TX DISABLE only) confirmed both halves
of the TX DISABLE/ENABLE pair are destructive to the firmware-trained
DP link.

v59 step-by-step lane-status probe:

  preserving PS4 DP TX lock; skip TX DISABLE                  ← v59 fired
    (no before/after-dig_tx-action=0 — DISABLE bypassed OK)
  after-dig_encoder-action=0x0c (DP_VIDEO_OFF)  f8=0xff f9=0x1b   ← OK
  after-dig_encoder-action=0x0f (SETUP)         f8=0xff f9=0x1b   ← OK
  after-dig_encoder-action=0x10 (PANEL_MODE)    f8=0xff f9=0x1b   ← OK
  before-dig_tx-action=1 (TX ENABLE)            f8=0xff f9=0x1b   ← still locked
  after-dig_tx-action=1  (TX ENABLE)            f8=0x0f f9=0x1a   ← *** ENABLE BROKE IT ***
  after-dig_encoder-action=0x0d (DP_VIDEO_ON)   f8=0x0f f9=0x1a

So skipping DISABLE preserved lane lock through DP_VIDEO_OFF and DIG
encoder SETUP/PANEL_MODE — but TX ENABLE then flipped 0x60f8 from 0xff
straight to 0x0f. Even more destructive than DISABLE was (which had
flipped to 0x9f).

Why ENABLE breaks an already-enabled PHY: amdgpu's
setup_dig_transmitter(ENABLE) reprograms the v5 args struct with
ucPhyId=UNIPHYA, ucLaneNum=4 (from dig_connector via v52 floor),
usSymClock=27000 (270 MHz, from dp_clock floor), ucDPLaneSet=0
(default voltage swing 0, pre-emphasis 0). PS4 firmware likely trained
the link with different swing/preemph values per lane (DPCD-driven
adaptive equalization), so when ATOM bytecode rewrites them to our
defaults, the receiver sees an electrically-different signal and drops
lock immediately.

This patch (v60) extends v59's "preserve firmware TX state" model:
also skip ATOM_TRANSMITTER_ACTION_ENABLE on Liverpool/Gladius DP.

Conditions are identical to v59 (same triple-condition gate):

  - asic_type == CHIP_LIVERPOOL || CHIP_GLADIUS
  - encoder mode is DP
  - connector != NULL

When the gate fires, log "ps4_atom: preserving PS4 DP TX lock; skip TX
ENABLE". The non-PS4/non-DP/no-connector paths fall through to the
normal ENABLE call.

Combined with v59 (DISABLE skip) and patch 0006 (link_train early
return), the modeset DPMS_OFF/ON cycle becomes for Liverpool DP:

  DPMS_OFF branch:
    DP_VIDEO_OFF                   ← runs (preserves lock per v58)
    dp_set_rx_power_state(D3)      ← runs (preserves lock per v58)
    [TX DISABLE skipped — v59]

  DPMS_ON branch:
    DIG SETUP                      ← runs (preserves lock per v58/v59)
    PANEL_MODE                     ← runs (preserves lock per v58/v59)
    [TX ENABLE skipped — v60]
    [link_train: early-return per patch 0006]
    DP_VIDEO_ON                    ← runs (effect on intact lock unknown)

The remaining unknown is DP_VIDEO_ON's effect on an intact lock. v58
showed it preserved f8=0x9f (broken state), but didn't test it on
0xff. v59 showed it preserved 0x0f (broken). v60 will be the first
boot where DP_VIDEO_ON runs against an intact 0xff lock.

Predictions for v60:

  Best case:
    - "preserving PS4 DP TX lock; skip TX DISABLE" fires
    - "preserving PS4 DP TX lock; skip TX ENABLE" fires
    - All probes through DP_VIDEO_ON show f8=0xff f9=0x1b
    - Bridge cq_wait_set chunk A passes fast (~30ms)
    - HDMI lights up

  Mixed:
    - DP_VIDEO_ON also flips f8 → v61 also gates DP_VIDEO_ON (or feeds
      it state-preserving args if possible)

  Worst:
    - Lock survives entire modeset, but bridge still hangs at chunk
      B (0x10f6) or chunk C (0x7204) — those are tolerated baseline
      timeouts but don't actually unblock HDMI scanout. Then the
      next investigation pivots to bridge-internal state.

If v60 lights HDMI: v59+v60 are the keepers. v53/v54 stay disabled.
The "preserve firmware-trained DP link" model is validated.

---
--- a/drivers/gpu/drm/amd/amdgpu/atombios_encoders.c
+++ b/drivers/gpu/drm/amd/amdgpu/atombios_encoders.c
@@ -1379,9 +1379,30 @@
 			}
 		}
 		/* enable the transmitter */
-		amdgpu_atombios_encoder_setup_dig_transmitter(encoder,
-						       ATOM_TRANSMITTER_ACTION_ENABLE,
-						       0, 0);
+		/* v60 (PS4 Liverpool/Gladius DP): v59 confirmed skipping
+		 * TX DISABLE preserved 0x60f8=0xff through DP_VIDEO_OFF / DIG
+		 * SETUP / PANEL_MODE — but TX ENABLE then flipped f8 from
+		 * 0xff to 0x0f (even more destructive than DISABLE was). The
+		 * firmware-trained PHY rejects amdgpu's ENABLE reprogramming
+		 * with our 4 lanes / 270 MHz / UNIPHYA / dpLaneSet=0 config
+		 * because BIOS used a different state. Skip TX ENABLE on PS4
+		 * DP encoders too — leave the firmware transmitter completely
+		 * untouched through the modeset cycle. */
+		{
+			struct amdgpu_device *adev_tx = drm_to_adev(encoder->dev);
+			bool ps4_internal_dp =
+				(adev_tx->asic_type == CHIP_LIVERPOOL ||
+				 adev_tx->asic_type == CHIP_GLADIUS) &&
+				ENCODER_MODE_IS_DP(amdgpu_atombios_encoder_get_encoder_mode(encoder)) &&
+				connector;
+
+			if (ps4_internal_dp)
+				pr_info("ps4_atom: preserving PS4 DP TX lock; skip TX ENABLE\n");
+			else
+				amdgpu_atombios_encoder_setup_dig_transmitter(encoder,
+								       ATOM_TRANSMITTER_ACTION_ENABLE,
+								       0, 0);
+		}
 		if (ENCODER_MODE_IS_DP(amdgpu_atombios_encoder_get_encoder_mode(encoder)) &&
 		    connector) {
 			/* DP_SET_POWER_D0 is set in amdgpu_atombios_dp_link_train */
